Dr. '''Richard Pan''' (born October 28, 1965<ref>[http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:mcvlPe2ZL44J:www.govbuddy.com/directory/CA/richard-pan/3152/+Richard+Pan+Gov+Buddy&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&source=www.google.com Assembly Member Richard Pan of California]</ref>) is an [[United States|American]] [[politician]] currently serving in the [[California State Assembly]]. He is a [[California Democratic Party|Democrat]] representing the [[California's 9th State Assembly district|9th district]], encompassing parts of [[Sacramento County, California|Sacramento]] and [[San Joaquin County, California|San Joaquin]] counties.  Dr. Pan is Vice-Chair of the California Assembly Veteran's Affairs Committee and serves on the committees on Health, Aging and Long-Term Care, and Accountability and Administrative Review.  He also is Chair of the Select Committee on Healthcare Workforce and Access to Care.<ref>http://www.assembly.ca.gov/acs/acsframeset8text.asp</ref>  He continues to practice at the The EFFORT Oak Park Community Clinic,<ref>http://www.theeffort.org/loc_oak_park.htm</ref> where he established the pediatric clinic while at [[UC Davis Medical Center|UC Davis Children's Hospital]].<ref>http://www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/children/partnerships_affiliations/TheEffort/index.html</ref>

Prior to being elected to the state assembly, he was a [[pediatrician]] and professor at the [[UC Davis Medical Center|UC Davis Children's Hospital]],<ref>http://www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/children/</ref> where he led the [[pediatrics|pediatric]] [[residency]] program.  Dr. Pan founded Communities and Health Professionals Together (formerly Communities and Physicians Together), a nationally recognized program that partners resident physicians with community associations to improve community health.<ref>http://cpt-online.weebly.com/index.html</ref>  In 2005, CPT received the Community Campus Partnerships for Health Award<ref>http://depts.washington.edu/ccph/awardsrecipients.html</ref> and in 2008, Dr. Pan received the [[Campus Compact]] Thomas Ehrlich Faculty Award for Service Learning<ref>http://www.compact.org/news/press-releases/campus-compact-honors-uc-davis-physician-for-innovative-partnerships-to-promote-community-health/201/</ref> for his work on CHPT.  Dr. Pan also taught community development at [[UC Davis]].<ref>http://communitydevelopment.ucdavis.edu/index.php</ref>

Expanding beyond his work to put doctors in touch with communities, Dr. Pan dedicated his private time to a number of local boards, organizations, and causes aimed at strengthening the community. He is a board member of the [[United Way of America|United Way]] California Capitol Region,<ref>http://www.yourlocalunitedway.org/home</ref> a past board member of BloodSource,<ref>http://www.bloodsource.org/</ref> a regional [[blood bank]], and served for six years as a Commissioner on the Sacramento [[California Proposition 10 (1998)|First 5 Commission]],<ref>http://www.sackids.saccounty.net/default.htm</ref> which supports programs for children 0–5 years.  He was a founding board member and chair of Healthy Kids Healthy Future,<ref>http://www.hkhf.org/</ref> a regional administrative agency that obtained health care coverage for over 65,000 children in [[Colusa County, California|Colusa]], [[El Dorado County, California|El Dorado]], [[Placer County, California|Placer]], [[Sacramento County, California|Sacramento]], and [[Yuba County, California|Yuba]] counties. He also was a founding member of the Sacramento Health Improvement Project,<ref>http://www.capitolhealthnetwork.org/CCHNNewsletterSpring2009.pdf</ref> a coalition of physicians, hospitals, clinics, and community activists working to strengthen the health care safety-net in [[Sacramento County, California|Sacramento County]].

Dr. Pan is a nationally recognized university educator.  In addition to teaching as a faculty member at UC Davis, he has published numerous papers on [[medical education in the United States|medical education]] and [[physician supply|physician workforce]].  He served on the [[American Medical Association]] Council on Medical Education<ref>http://www.ama-assn.org/ama/pub/about-ama/our-people/ama-councils/council-medical-education.page?</ref> and on the board of the [[Accreditation Council on Graduate Medical Education]],<ref>http://www.acgme.org/acWebsite/annRep/an_2008-09AnnRep.pdf</ref> which oversees physician [[residency]] education in the United States.  He also was an [[Academic Pediatric Association|Ambulatory Pediatric Association]] National Pediatric Faculty Development Scholar.

Dr. Pan has received many awards for his community and professional leadership including the UC Davis Chancellor’s Award for Diversity and Community,<ref>http://dateline.ucdavis.edu/dl_detail.lasso?id=7370</ref> the [[Medical Board of California]] Physician Humanitarian Award,<ref>http://www.medbd.ca.gov/licensee/physician_humanitarian_recipients.html</ref> the [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] [[Abraham Jacobi]] Memorial Award for lifetime achievement in pediatrics, the Sierra Sacramento Valley Medical Society Medical Honor Award,<ref>http://www.ssvms.org/ssv_medicine/archives/2008/01/articles/0801-meet.pdf</ref> the California School Nurses Organization Lydia Smiley Award,<ref>http://www.ucdmc.ucdavis.edu/welcome/features/20090415_Pan_award/index.html</ref><ref>http://www.csno.org/docs/2009%20Conference%20Bulletin.pdf</ref> the [[United Way of America|United Way]] California Capitol Region Clarence La Rue Outstanding Volunteer Award, and the Child Abuse Prevention Council of Sacramento Hearts and Hands Award.

Dr. Pan received a [[B.A.]] in [[Biophysics]] at [[The Johns Hopkins University]], a [[M.D.]] at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] entering into the [[Alpha Omega Alpha]] Honor Medical Society, and a [[Master of Public Health|M.P.H.]] at [[Harvard University]].  He completed his pediatric [[residency]] at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] also serving as Chief Resident in Pediatrics and was a Primary Care Research Fellow and Anne Dyson Pediatric Advocacy Fellow at [[Children's Hospital Boston]].  He also was a [[California HealthCare Foundation]] Health Care Leadership Fellow.<ref>http://futurehealth.ucsf.edu/Public/Leadership-Programs/Home.aspx?pid=145</ref>

Dr. Pan lives in Sacramento with his wife and two children.  Dr. Pan's parents were immigrants to the United States from Taiwan.

